  "prompt": "What is the difference between a bond and a debenture in the UK?",
  "response": "In the UK, while bonds and debentures are both types of debt instruments, they have some key differences:\n\nBonds:\n1. Typically issued by governments or corporations\n2. Usually secured against specific assets\n3. Generally considered lower risk\n4. Often have lower interest rates due to lower risk\n5. Can be traded on public markets\n6. May have government or institutional backing\n\nDebentures:\n1. Primarily issued by corporations\n2. Typically unsecured, meaning they are not backed by specific collateral\n3. Higher risk compared to bonds\n4. Generally offer higher interest rates to compensate for increased risk\n5. Can be convertible or non-convertible into company shares\n6. Rely on the issuing company's creditworthiness\n7. Often used for medium to long-term corporate financing\n\nKey distinctions:\n- Security: Bonds are usually secured, while debentures are typically unsecured\n- Risk profile: Bonds are generally lower risk compared to debentures\n- Interest rates: Debentures often offer higher returns to reflect greater risk\n- Flexibility: Debentures may have more flexible terms, such as convertibility\n\nBoth instruments are ways for organizations to raise capital by borrowing money from investors.",
